[normal]5.0[bold]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Whether the current regulatory regime covering such activity is adequate;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]5.1
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The UK has a long history of regulating onshore hydrocarbon exploration and production through the DECC onshore licen
[normal]s
[normal]ing regime, local or minerals planning regime, 
[normal]Coal Authority, 
[normal]Environment Agency or Natural Resource Wales licen
[normal]s
[normal]ing provisions and the Health and Safety Executive. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]5.2
[normal]              
[normal]The
[normal] current
[normal] regulatory
[normal] regime is considered to provide robust protection to the environment, local communities and workforce
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]5.3
[normal]              
[normal]Notwithstanding the previous statement 
[normal]there is a considerable amount of duplication both in the information being submitted and the number of public consultations required throughout the 
[normal]planning
[normal] and permitting regime that introduces significant uncertainty, costs and time delays to the well planning process.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]5.4
[normal]              
[normal]A clarification of responsibilities of each of the regulators between surface and sub-surface development and a single application for the permitting of well operations to remove the duplication currently inherent in the permitting system would be of significa
[normal]nt benefit to 
[normal]op
[normal]erators and would speed up the exploration and 
[normal]appraisal
[normal] of the shale resource.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]6.0[bold]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
