[normal]8.5
[normal]% of the total area of Wales currently licensed for oil and gas exploration it is difficult to estimate the potential impact of future shale gas development
[normal].  A
[normal]s previously stated the range of potential outcomes 
[normal]varies 
[normal]from almost nothing to very significant.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]6.2
[normal]              
[normal]The US example and recent reports by the Institute of Directors suggest that in the success case the unconventional hydrocarbons industry would benefit the UK, including Wales
[normal],
[normal] due to:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]6.3
[normal]              
[normal]The exact scale of th
[normal]e benefits would be directly proportional to the eventual scale of the industry in the UK, however given the UK’s leading role in unconventional development the first mover advantage could result in the export of skills, processes and supply chain to others that follow in the European or North African markets.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]6.4
[normal]              
[normal]Ignoring effects on gas price on primary energy production the benefits of an increased supply of low cost ethane
[normal],
[normal] via domestic shale gas production
[normal],
[normal] could have game changing effect on the petrochemicals industry.  A 2011 report by the American Chemicals Council modelled the impacts of a 25% increase in ethane availability on the petrochemicals industry in the US and concluded the following:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]6.5
[normal]              
[normal]While no-one is suggesting a direct replication of this in the UK or Wales 
[normal]it does go some way to demonstrating the transformational effect that domestic shale gas could have on one particular sector of the economy.  
